!ROLES PHIL CARL TASK EUGENE ERNESTO BERNADETTE JAYNE LOUIE

-9-
!ACT One

!SCENE 1 
(The scene is a restaurant kitchen. Upstage right are two swinging doors with round windows which lead to a suggested dining room. Upstage left is a counter where the chef places prepared food to be delivered to the customers. The actual cooking area is suggested offstage behind this counter. Downstage left is the door to the back alley which opens upstage. Upstage center is a door with a glass window labeled "office." Downstage right is the heavy oversized door of the walk-in refrigerator. A small table and two chairs are center stage and may be moved to suit the action. Next to the office door is a wall phone.)
(AT RISE: As the LIGHTS come up we see CARL and PHIL standing in the kitchen.)


CARL. We don't know how to run a restaurant.
PHIL. What's to know? People come in, we feed them, they give us money. We'll make a fortune.
CARL. If it's so easy, why doesn't everyone do it?
PHIL. Because not everyone has a wealthy big shot loaning them the money.
CARL. His terms are too tough.
PHIL. It's all figured out. What we make on the food goes to pay back the loan. Meanwhile we survive on our tips.
CARL. What tips?

-10-
PHIL. You are going to be the waiter, Carl.
CARL. I don't know how to be a waiter.
PHIL. Here's your waiting lesson, Carl: how's the food? Here's your check. Have a nice day. Got it?
CARL. Wouldn't something like a laundry be easier to run? Everybody needs a laundry.
PHIL. What sounds better to you, Carl the restaurateur or Carl the laundry mat?
CARL. I wish we never quit the post office.
PHIL. Look, we are doing this for three reasons: money, money and money. Forget about the post office they'll always need someone to lose the mail.
CARL. Right.
PHIL. All the money is moving to one place, the top, and the people at the top are working day and night to get the rest. Don't you want to be part of the big pile at the top? This is the big time. Trust me, I've examined all the angles.
CARL. I trust you Phil, I just have some questions.
PHIL. Throw 'em at me.
CARL. Do we have to get some sort of license from the city? Don't we need to advertise? Who's going to make the food?
PHIL. Whoa! You're getting way ahead of yourself. We decide those things as they come up. One thing at a time. You either trust my business sense or you don't.
CARL. I'm sorry.
PHIL. No offense taken. Now let's sign this ten year lease.


(THEY begin to sign the lease.)

-11-
CARL. What are we going to name the restaurant?
PHIL. Good question. First I thought "Carl's" might be a good name but somehow it seemed limp and ineffectual, know what I mean?
CARL. Yes.
PHIL. So I thought the next logical choice would be "Phil's." What do you think?
CARL. It would be easy for you to remember.


(A POLICEMAN in a mounted patrol uniform sticks his head in from the dining room. HE has the bridle of his horse in his hand.)


TASK. Excuse me?
CARL. Who are you?
TASK. Officer Task, mounted patrol unit. How much longer are we going to have to wait out here?
PHIL. For what?
TASK. A little service.
CARL. We're not open yet.
TASK. It's almost one o'clock, people like to eat lunch around noon.
PHIL. We're just now signing the lease.
TASK. But I'm really hungry.
CARL. (Lifts his lunch sack.) Want some of my sandwich?
TASK. What kind?
CARL. Salami.
TASK. Mustard?
CARL. Yes.
TASK. How much?
PHIL. Two bucks.

-12-
TASK. For a crummy sandwich?
PHIL. Go sit down, we'll bring it out to you.
TASK. (Thinks it over.) Okay. (TASK backs his horse up.) C'mon girl, back, back.
PHIL. How about that, we aren't even open and we're making a profit.
CARL. This sandwich is a little squished.


(CARL tries to make it flat, PHIL takes it from him.)


PHIL. This is a good omen, I can feel it.


(PHIL takes the sandwich into the dining room. The PHONE rings and CARL answers it.)


CARL. Hello Phil's. Yes we are hiring today. I'm not sure.


(PHIL re-enters.)


CARL. Phil? There is someone on the phone who wants to know if we will hire the handicapped?
PHIL. No.
CARL. (Speaks back into the phone.) No. (Pause.) He wants to know why.
PHIL. Does it look like we have room for wheelchairs around here? Give me the phone. Hello? I'm sorry we can't help but maybe we can send you a small donation ... (Pause.) How much is substantially lower? (Pause.) On second thought, send him by. He's a she? Well send him by anyway. (PHIL hangs up.)

-13-
PHIL. We just got a chef for about half the going wage. I wonder what her handicap is?
CARL. She golfs too?


(A young MAN with a large nose enters.)


EUGENE. Excuse me, is this where the interviews are being conducted?
CARL. Yes it is, Phil we have a young man here who ...
PHIL. I have eyes in my skull, Carl. What can we do for you?
EUGENE. I would like to apply for a waiting position.
PHIL. We don't need a waiter.
EUGENE. How are you going to run a restaurant without waiters?
PHIL. My partner here is going to be the waiter.
EUGENE. Has he been a waiter before?
PHIL. He knows what it takes.
EUGENE. (Approaches Carl.) Where have you worked?
CARL. No place you would know.
EUGENE. On which side of the plate do you place the fork?
CARL. You mean on the table?
EUGENE. You're stalling.
CARL. No I'm not ...
EUGENE. (Snapping his fingers.) Quickly!
CARL. The right?
EUGENE. Just as I thought.
CARL. Can I have another guess?
EUGENE. It belongs on the left.
CARL. Your left or my left?

-14-
EUGENE. Since good service is essential to the success of any restaurant I suggest you seek professional training before you attempt to open. Good day.
CARL. Wait a second! What is your name?
EUGENE. Eugene.
CARL. Could you wait out in the dining room for a moment?
EUGENE. I suppose. (EUGENE exits.)
CARL. He knows what he's talking about, Phil.
PHIL. You'll be fine.
CARL. But what about all the mistakes I'll make before I get it right? We don't want to get a bad reputation before we work out all the bugs.
PHIL. We don't need a big payroll.
CARL. We're saving with the impaired chef, remember?
PHIL. Okay, we'll use him in the beginning, then fire him.
EUGENE. (Re-enters.) I don't have all day, gentlemen.
CARL. Good news Eugene, you're hired.
PHIL. Work with Carl, teach him the ropes.
EUGENE. Very well.
CARL. Welcome aboard, sure is nice to have a professional waiter.
EUGENE. No offense, but I am really a professional actor. I'll work here until I'm discovered and become a star.
PHIL. Can you just be here on Monday?
EUGENE. Until then, ciao! (EUGENE exits.)
CARL. Wow, an actor.
PHIL. Have you been inhaling something?
CARL. Do you remember him from any movies?
PHIL. If he's an actor I'm an avocado.

-15-
CARL. Just think, people can come in here and be served by a real live actor!
PHIL. How does he hope to be an actor? Did you get a load of that nose?
CARL. He's really handsome except for that nose.
PHIL. Too bad it's in the middle of his face. Looks like he's growing a wing.


(ERNESTO enters cautiously, holding a briefcase.)


PHIL. May I help you?
ERNESTO. Busboy.
PHIL. I beg your pardon?
ERNESTO. Busboy.
PHIL. You want to be a busboy?
ERNESTO. Jes.
PHIL. Here, fill out an application.


(ERNESTO examines the paper and hands it back to Phil.)


PHIL. What is your name?
ERNESTO. Ernesto Santiago.
PHIL. (Fills in the application.) Ernesto Santiago. Where are you from?
ERNESTO. Er, Norway.
PHIL. Norway?
ERNESTO. Jes, Norway.
PHIL. (Writes down Norway.) Where have you worked before?
ERNESTO. In restaurants, jes.
PHIL. Did you go to school?
ERNESTO. School?

-16-
PHIL. Jes. I mean yes.
ERNESTO. Er, the University of of, Oslo. Jes the University of Oslo. Jes.
PHIL. What did you study?
ERNESTO. Study?
PHIL. Jes.
ERNESTO. English.
PHIL. That's a very nice suit.
ERNESTO. Thank you very much. Mr. Giamamoni gave it to me.
PHIL. Mr. Giamamoni? Our investor? Why didn't you say so? Can you start on Monday?
ERNESTO. Monday?
PHIL. Jes!
ERNESTO. Jes, see you Monday. Gracias! (ERNESTO exits.)
PHIL. He should be fine, don't you think?
CARL. Guess what? The word for thank you is the same in Norwegian and Spanish.
PHIL. Makes sense, they share a border.


(BERNADETTE enters and hands a piece of paper to Phil. HE reads it.)


PHIL. Oh, you are a chef. Please sit down.


(BERNADETTE remains standing.)


PHIL. Would you like a seat?


(BERNADETTE remains standing.)

-17-
PHIL. Did you hear me?


(BERNADETTE hands him another note.)


PHIL. "I am from the Occupational Placement Institute."
CARL. This must be the impaired chef!


(BERNADETTE hands Phil another note.)


PHIL. Another note.
CARL. (Takes the note and reads aloud.) "Lost my hearing ten years ago when gun accidently discharged near my head while hunting for wild mushrooms but can read lips very well." Oh, she reads lips!


(The BOYS begin to speak in a loud and animated manner.)


CARL. ^WHAT ^IS ^YOUR ^NAME?
PHIL. (Looking at first note.) Says here Bernadette.
CARL. ^PLEASED ^TO ^MEET ^YOU ^BERNADETTE.
PHIL. ^WE ^WANT ^YOU ^TO ^COOK ^WHATEVER ^YOU ^DO ^BEST.
CARL. ^WE ^DON'T ^KNOW ^WHAT ^WE ^ARE ^DOING.
PHIL. ^WHY ^DID ^YOU ^SAY ^THAT?
CARL. ^SHE ^CAN ^SEE ^THAT, ^SHE'S ^NOT ^BLIND ^TOO.
PHIL. ^WHY ^ARE ^YOU ^SCREAMING ^AT ^ME? I'M ^NOT ^DEAF.
CARL. ^YOU'^RE ^SCREAMING ^AT ^ME.


(BERNADETTE hands Phil another note.)

-18-
PHIL. (Reads aloud.) "^MY ^FATHER ^WAS ^THE ^FAMOUS ^NATURALIST, ^EWELL ^SIMEON." ^YOUR ^FATHER ^WAS ^MR. ^ROUGHAGE?


(BERNADETTE nods)


CARL. I ^WATCHED ^HIM ^ON ^PUBLIC ^TELEVISION! (CARL begins to imitate a television announcer.) ^REMEMBER: ^OAT ^BRAN ^IS ^GOD'S ^GIFT ^TO ^YOUR ^COLON!


(BERNADETTE nods and smiles.)


CARL. ^REMEMBER: ^BIG ^FECES ^MEAN ^LITTLE ^HOSPITALS.
PHIL. ^OKAY ^CARL, ^THAT'S ^ENOUGH.
CARL. ^IF ^IT'S ^ROUGH ^GOING ^DOWN,
PHIL. ^CARL, ^QUIET!


(BERNADETTE hands Phil another note.)


PHIL. ^MY ^FATHER ^TAUGHT ^ME ^ALL ^ABOUT ^NATURAL ^FOODS ^AND I ^HAVE ^PERFECTED ^GOURMET ^TECHNIQUES ^TO ^PREPARE ^THEM.
CARL. I ^SURE ^WAS ^SORRY ^WHEN ^YOUR ^FATHER ^DIED ^RIGHT ^IN ^THE ^MIDDLE ^OF ^THAT ^SHOW.



(BERNADETTE nods sadly.)

-19-
CARL. ^MUST ^HAVE ^BEEN ^ALL ^THOSE ^CIGARETTES, ^HE ^ALWAYS ^HAD ^ONE ^GOING.


(TASK sticks his head in from the dining room and sees how everyone is talking.)


PHIL. ^BERNADETTE, ^CAN ^YOU ^START ^MONDAY? ^WE ^WANT ^TO ^OPEN ^ON ^MONDAY?


(BERNADETTE nods.)


PHIL. ^TERRIFIC! ^CARL, ^SHOW ^BERNADETTE ^WHERE ^SHE'^LL ^BE ^COOKING.
CARL. ^SURE ^THING, ^PHIL! ^BERNADETTE, ^RIGHT ^THIS ^WAY!


(The PHONE rings.)


PHIL. I'^LL ^GET ^IT!
CARL. ^OKAY ^PHIL!
TASK. ^COULD I ^GET ^MY ^CHECK ^PLEASE!!!
PHIL. ^HELLO, ^PHIL'S!


-20-
!SCENE 2
(Phil's is now in business but the kitchen is quiet. CARL, ERNESTO and BERNADETTE are standing around but PHIL is pacing nervously.)


PHIL. I'm a wreck.
CARL. Give it time.
PHIL. We've been open three weeks, don't you think public curiosity has pretty much peaked by now?
PHIL. At least we have Mr. Giamamoni's business.
EUGENE. (Angrily enters the kitchen with some dirty plates.) Just who does he think he is? I'd like to feed him his dinner through his nose!
PHIL. Not everyone can eat like you Eugene, besides, he happens to be the man who loaned us the money for this place.
EUGENE. You'd think he could say thank you just once.
PHIL. I'd take twenty more just like him in my dining room.
EUGENE. Twenty more of him and the world would spontaneously combust. (EUGENE rings a small bell on the counter.) Next course, table one please.
PHIL. Why aren't we busy? It just doesn't make sense.
EUGENE. Nothing makes sense around here. For instance, why do I have to ring a bell every time I order when the chef is deaf?


(EUGENE exits to the dining room as PHIL shouts.)

-21-
PHIL. Because we are trying to run this place in a professional manner!
CARL. I've come up with an idea.
PHIL. What is it now?
CARL. I've been thinking how some places become known for their house specialities so I invented a special drink. You light it on fire when you serve it.
PHIL. People won't want to put their faces in a glass of fire, Carl.
CARL. You blow it out when you present it. It looks very festive.
PHIL. What goes in it?
CARL. All different liquors, that's why it's so flammable. Just one of them will make you silly, that's how I came up with the name, Flaming Idiots, and look at this! (CARL reaches into the office and pulls out a signboard.) Remember Howard, the guy who makes the signs at the post office?
PHIL. The ones no one can ever read?
CARL. He's gotten better. Turn around and close your eyes.
PHIL. Just show me the sign.


(CARL shows the sign which is in U.S. Postal Service motif complete with bald eagles. It reads: HOME OF FLAMING IDIOTS.)


CARL. What do you think?
PHIL. (A long pause.) I like it. Put it in the front window.
CARL. Great! (CARL runs into the dining room.)
PHIL. Don't run in the dining room, Carl!

-22-
ERNESTO. I think that is a very stupid thing.
PHIL. No one asked you.
ERNESTO. I don't make much the money here.
PHIL. No one is, Ernesto, but you are making more than if you were back in the third world.
ERNESTO. I work in the restaurants before very busy. I no make the money here. Before, jes, now, no.
PHIL. Where did you work before?
ERNESTO. The Zippy's.
PHIL. Zippy's is a very popular place.
ERNESTO. Mr. Zippy he became the enemy of me! (ERNESTO spits angrily on the floor.)
PHIL. Ernesto.
ERNESTO. Jes?
PHIL. Don't spit on my floor.
ERNESTO. Sorry.
PHIL. Okay.
ERNESTO. I worked for the Mr. Zippy for over seven years.
PHIL. That's a long time.
ERNESTO. Jes. Then one day, Mr. Zippy says to me, Ernesto, you no more work for me the Mr. Zippy any more!
ERNESTO. (Spits angrily on the floor.) Oops. I will wipe this up. Mr. Zippy he destroyed me! He destroyed my family! I am so very angry right now I could spit! If I could. The busboys make very much money at the Zippy's, this place, Phil's, stinks!
PHIL. Zippy's has been in business a long time because a famous bad man was killed while eating his dinner and I think you are lucky to have a job at all because I'm about this close to going with Carl's idea and turning this place into a laundry.

-23-
ERNESTO. What!
PHIL. Where would you rather work, a restaurant or a laundry?


(ERNESTO drops to his knees and clutches PHIL'S ankles.)


ERNESTO. I am so sorry Mr. Phil! I am so sorry! I don't want to do it but Mr. Giamamoni ask me to do it! He gives me money for my family! That is why I switch the money for him! I need money for my family!
PHIL. What the heck are you talking about?
ERNESTO. The money laundry scheme!
PHIL. The what?
ERNESTO. You're not talking about the scheme with the money laundry here?
PHIL. No.
ERNESTO. Oh. Then never mind what I say. (ERNESTO crawls out sheepishly.)
PHIL. Is it something I do or am I just a magnet for lunatics?
CARL. (Enters.) Sign's in place. Let's give Mr. Giamamoni a Flaming Idiot when he finishes his seven tuber root casserole.
PHIL. Have you ever eaten at Zippy's?
CARL. No way, too expensive. That's where Cy Manamalancia was shot.
PHIL. I know. The table where it happened is booked for two years solid.
CARL. Can you imagine getting shot in a restaurant?

-24-
PHIL. If we don't pay some bills soon we won't have to use our imaginations.
CARL. This is just like how I felt when I saw a woman today with her skirt over her head.
PHIL. Some people have no fashion sense.
CARL. It wasn't on purpose, her shoulder bag must have caught the hem of her skirt because it was hitched up and she was all exposed.
PHIL. Did you tell her?
CARL. I couldn't, I was on the bus. I tried to do some sign language out the window but she just stared at me like I was an idiot. Now I know how she felt.
PHIL. Like you have a skirt up over your head?
CARL. No, like I'm stuck on a bus! The big bus of life! I don't know where I'm going and I can't get off and I see everything going on out my window but I can't do anything about it and nobody can hear me scream!
PHIL. The bus will say right on the front where it is going Carl. Just look at the front before you get on ...
CARL. You're on the bus with me! It's you and me and this restaurant is the bus and we can't get off! We have to do something!
PHIL. Carl, what has happened to your optimistic spirit? Sure, we are at a crucial point in our development but if we get through it we will have a much greater chance for success.
CARL. You think so?


(EUGENE re-enters.)


PHIL. Without a doubt. Think about it, what if Thomas Jefferson had been afraid of lightning? He never would have tied the bulb to his kite and we wouldn't have electricity. What if Alexander the Great Bell had gotten a wrong number the first time he tried his telephone, would he have given up?

-25-
EUGENE. What if the Wright Brothers had insisted upon in-flight movies?
PHIL. Exactly! They weren't afraid to take a chance.
CARL. I just wish we were successful.
PHIL. If wishes were horses, beggars would ride, Carl.
CARL. What?
PHIL. It's a saying. If wishes were horses, beggars would ride.
CARL. What does it mean?
PHIL. It means we have to take action.
CARL. If wishes had horses ...
PHIL. No, if wishes were horses.
CARL. If wishes were horses, beggars would die.
EUGENE. Not die, hide.
PHIL. Not hide, ride. Why would beggars hide?
EUGENE. Because the horses would be coming and they would be afraid of them.
PHIL. But they want the horses so that they can ride.
CARL. Where would they ride? To better places to beg?
PHIL. What it means is that if wishes came true, then even beggars would have what they wished for.
CARL. I think if I were a beggar a horse would be the last thing I would wish for.
EUGENE. I adore horses.
PHIL. You guys are missing the point.
EUGENE. I would ride off into the sunset.
CARL. I would wish for something really expensive so that I could sell it.

-26-
EUGENE. Why not just wish for the money so that you don't have to sell anything?
CARL. Okay. I wish I had a grillion dollars.
EUGENE. And I wish Giamamoni was dead.
PHIL. If I found a big rock, could you guys drop it on my head?


(JAYNE enters. Her shoulder bag has hitched her skirt up over her head. ERNESTO has followed her in.)


JAYNE. Pardon me.
CARL. It's her!
ERNESTO. I love America!
JAYNE. I'm Jayne Fryman from the Daily Local News Dispatch Vigilant Courier. I'm with advertising and I see that you have a new business here and I was wondering if you were interested in seeing a little exposure.
PHIL. Er, we really haven't thought about it.
EUGENE. The work has been endless.
CARL. But the end is in sight.
JAYNE. May I leave my card?
PHIL. Sure.
JAYNE. Just thought I'd take a chance and pop in. If I had my sample book I would show you everything.
EUGENE. That would've been nice.
JAYNE. I must hurry along now. I'm afraid I've got a little behind. (JAYNE exits.)
CARL. Maybe that's what we need to do, Phil, advertise.

-27-
PHIL. We could hang a sign on her, she knows how to get attention. No, I'm afraid even small ads cost a lot of money.
EUGENE. You could save a lot of money if you didn't let so many people eat for free. You give away the house.
CARL. But they're friends.
EUGENE. Why don't you work out some kind of barter system?
PHIL. Because most of them work for the post office.
EUGENE. All of them? Look at the reservations tonight. Uncle Bob, eight o'clock.
PHIL. That's different, Bob's a relative.
EUGENE. What does he do for a living?
PHIL. He works for the county morgue.
EUGENE. Maybe that's not a good example ...
CARL. Maybe he could inspect our meat?
EUGENE. How about we borrow a bunch of bodies and put them around the dining room so we look busy.
PHIL. (Suddenly freezes with an idea.) Better yet ... Eugene, there must be something you could be doing in the dining room.
EUGENE. Not really.
PHIL. I'm sure if you looked you could find something.
EUGENE. I already did.


(PHIL goes into the dining room. Suddenly there is a terrific crash. PHIL re-enters.)


PHIL. It's a mess out there.
EUGENE. Right. (HE exits.)
PHIL. Go help him Ernesto

-28-
ERNESTO. This is a very stupido restaurante. (HE exits.)
CARL. Maybe Eugene is right about not giving so much away.
PHIL. He had an even better idea but he didn't know it. Maybe we can use Uncle Bob after all. What would happen if someone got shot in Phil's Restaurant?
CARL. You can't shoot your Uncle Bob!
PHIL. Not Bob, someone else. Think about it, Zippy's has been in business all these years because Manamalancia got shot there, what if a mobster got shot here.
CARL. I'm not killing anybody.
PHIL. That's it exactly! We'll kill a body. What if we borrowed a body from Bob at the morgue? A body with no family, a John Doe? I bet they get them all the time. We take the body and put it at our best table on a Saturday night then hire someone to walk up behind it in the middle of dinner and blammo!
CARL. (Jumps.) Blammo?
PHIL. Blammo! The body falls, the gunman runs out, we make the papers and Phil's is a success just like Zippy's!
CARL. We can't do that!
PHIL. Why not?
CARL. It would be murder!
PHIL. No it wouldn't, the guy's already dead.
CARL. But we would be hiring someone to commit murder.


PHIL. Only if he shoots someone who's alive, this guy's already dead.
CARL. There must be something wrong with this.

-29-
PHIL. I tell you it's a brainstorm! The cops will come and figure it had to be someone important or else he wouldn't have been shot, they'll haul him off to the morgue ... hey ... we'll even get free delivery!
CARL. Will Bob go for this?
PHIL. We'll barter with him, Bob would kill himself for a free meal.
EUGENE. (Re-enters.) Giomamoni's finished.
PHIL. Let's give him your Flaming Idiot, Carl.
CARL.(Picks up the drink.) I don't feel good about this.
PHIL. Our backs are against the wall, we have to do something. That looks very pretty.
CARL. Yeah, it looks so pretty I think I'm going to cry.


(CARL begins to light the drink as THEY both exit to the dining room. ERNESTO enters as they go out with his briefcase which HE switches with an identical one hidden in the walk-in. A loud CRASH is heard from the dining room and CARL and PHIL dash back into the kitchen.)


PHIL. Why weren't you more careful!
CARL. It was very top-heavy!
PHIL. Let's just put Giamamoni out! (PHIL grabs the fire extinguisher and THEY dash back out.)

-30-
!SCENE 3
(CARL sits at the table as the PHONE rings. After four rings, PHIL enters. HE moves toward the phone just as it stops ringing. HE looks at CARL, shrugs and begins talking excitedly.)


PHIL. We're all set! I just had a talk with Bob and he's going to come through. It's going to cost us free dinners from now until doomsday but if our plan works it won't matter. See, the morgue is closed weekends except for deliveries and Bob is the only one there so Friday night when he gets off he's going to bring us a body and leave it for us in the walk-in. We'll use it Saturday night and the cops will take it back to him Sunday and no one will even miss it. What do you think of that?
CARL. What?
PHIL. I said what do you think?
CARL. What?
PHIL. Didn't you hear me?
CARL. What?
PHIL. ^WHAT'S ^THE ^MATTER ^WITH ^YOU!
CARL. Just a second. (CARL removes something from his ears.)
PHIL. What are those?
CARL. Earplugs. I've been seeing what it's like to be Bernadette.
PHIL. What are you talking about?
CARL. I wanted to see what it was like to be deaf. It's really weird, you can't hear anything.

-31-
PHIL. Maybe you would like to show Bernadette what it's like to be brain damaged! Do you remember what you are supposed to be doing here?
CARL. Taking reservations.
PHIL. And have you taken any?
CARL. Nobody's called.
PHIL. And how would you know that?
CARL. Because I've been here all day.
PHIL. I'm sure having an imbecile for a partner could be used to my advantage.
CARL. Give it time, you'll think of something. (CARL starts to put the earplugs back in.)
PHIL. ^PUT ^THOSE ^THINGS ^AWAY!


(CARL places them in a box on the table.)


PHIL. A body is being delivered here on Friday.
CARL. We're really doing it?
PHIL. Now we have to find a hit-man.
CARL. Can't we ask a friend to do it?
PHIL. What do you think this is Carl, theatre? Are we actors on a stage here? We don't want someone who's going to get caught, we need a pro who will think he's doing the real thing.
CARL. Where do we get a real hit-man?
PHIL. One thing's for sure we won't have a lot to pay him. We'll show him how easy the job will be, then make a deal with him.
CARL. Maybe we can barter for free meals.
PHIL. I don't think we are going to find a killer willing to work for a pine cone salad, Carl.

-32-
(EUGENE and ERNESTO enter.)


PHIL. What are you guys doing here so early?
EUGENE. I have to rehearse.
PHIL. Rehearse what?
EUGENE. The Great Kyle Wagner is holding auditions for his new theater.
PHIL. The great who?
EUGENE. Only the greatest director of all time. He's a mythical, reclusive figure. I need a big space to rehearse.
PHIL. This is a place of business, Eugene.
CARL. Can we be your audience?
EUGENE. Could you!
PHIL. Carl!
EUGENE. This will only take a few minutes, I could really use the practice.
PHIL. We don't have time for this.
CARL. Please, Phil?
PHIL. Be quick about it.
EUGENE. (Pulls a cape and skull from his bag.) Thank you, you won't regret this.
PHIL. For some reason I already am.
EUGENE. I'm really nervous, I'm having a mini anxiety attack.
